EDIT: To be clear this applies to just ONE show in the entire tour.  ALL OTHER SHOWS are going ahead as planned. 🧡

As many of you know, since Covid-19 the live concert industry has been incredibly challenged and touring has become a financial and logistical nightmare for many musicians. 
Sadly, my upcoming Australian tour has been severely impacted by those challenges and as a result, we’ve had to make the terribly difficult decision to cancel the Gold Coast date on the Australian leg of my ‘Do You Remember?’ tour. 

Although my team and I agonized over the best way to try to make the numbers work, it became clear that although my promoter was ambitious in booking me into so many venues and large spaces, we simply hadn't sold enough tickets overall to break even and that was putting the entire Australian leg of the tour in jeopardy unless we made some changes.
 
It was suggested to me to cancel several cities, or postpone the Australian tour altogether - but I refused to do that. People are flying in from all over the world to come to this tour and I couldn’t live with myself if I caused that kind of chaos to their lives. 

Usually when something like this happens, an artist will put out a polite, vague excuse like ’scheduling conflicts’ or ‘unforeseen circumstances’ but I have too much respect for you to do that. I’ve always been truthful and this is the reality of the music industry in 2022.

It’s a strange time to be touring. Covid seems to have affected touring markets it different ways. In the UK we had to add six more shows. Similarly in the USA, I’m about to add 4 more dates. For whatever reason this is the situation in Australia for many artists and we all have to evolve and adapt to these changing times.  If you have purchased a ticket to the Gold Coast show, I've been told Ticketek will contact you directly about a refund. 

I love you folks - it pains me to have to disappoint anyone, especially those in my home state, but I hope you know we are working night and day to put on the best possible show. Bringing this music to you, live, after being away so long, is a dream come true and a dream worth fighting for. 

Love
Darren

The one night in 26 shows that I wore an alternate color lace shirt for the first act.  This is a purple version of the black ones.  I have 6 of everything for the main opening look. 6 lace shirts, 6 neoprene trousers, 6 bow ties etc. 3 pairs of my tall boots.  6 of the rhinestone belts. But there were two of this purple (lavender actually) lace shirt, sourced as an alternate but we decided to go with all black. Last night at the DC show I decided to wear it. Since the venue was so unique and it was our second last show I figured I’d break the rules. Also it’s an homage to the few nights MJ wore a black then red version of the ‘Bad Tour’ shirt before settling on the silver one he wore on every date. Photo by Zachary D

3 continents- 26 shows - The Do You Remember Tour has finally come to an end. It’s going to take me a long time to process this incredible experience.  I’m so grateful to this touring family who literally lifted me and each other up every day to put on the best possible shows of our lives for the sole purpose of creating joy.  I’m so grateful to every person who bought a ticket to a show. Your love and support meant everything. You are the reason all of this exists.  Excuse me while I cry for a while. Don’t worry - they’re tears of joy. ( Thanks Trevor, Maddy, Ei, Luke, Matt, Paul, Claire, Dick, Lisa, Nathan, Saige, Alex and Tracey and all our Australian band and crew!)
And just like that .. it’s over.  Photo by dirtypuppydaddy

Never in my entire career has art ever immitated life more than this year.
I'm grateful to film maker Andrew Huebscher for his passion for 'Feels Like It's Over' which resulted in me shooting this video just days before I left for the 'Do You Remember?' tour. I'm forever indebted to Andrew for his oustanding direction and cinematography and to my wonderful scene parter, Casey James - who laughed with me and patiently held me while I cried for three days straight as we made this short film.
This is the end of an era in so many ways. I poured my soul into this album, this tour and into people I met along the way and yes, I got my heart broken in the end. Was it worth it? I dont know. But it's all real. I don't know how to be any other way.

Having a Coke with You - Frank O’Hara 
  Having a Coke with you is even more fun than going to San Sebastian, Irún, Hendaye, Biarritz, Bayonne
or being sick to my stomach on the Travesera de Gracia in Barcelona
partly because in your orange shirt you look like a better happier St. Sebastian
partly because of my love for you, partly because of your love for yoghurt
partly because of the fluorescent orange tulips around the birches
partly because of the secrecy our smiles take on before people and statuary
it is hard to believe when I’m with you that there can be anything as still
as solemn as unpleasantly definitive as statuary when right in front of it
in the warm New York 4 o’clock light we are drifting back and forth
between each other like a tree breathing through its spectacles
and the portrait show seems to have no faces in it at all, just paint
you suddenly wonder why in the world anyone ever did them
                                                                                                              I look
at you and I would rather look at you than all the portraits in the world
except possibly for the Polish Rider occasionally and anyway it’s in the Frick
which thank heavens you haven’t gone to yet so we can go together for the first time
and the fact that you move so beautifully more or less takes care of Futurism
just as at home I never think of the Nude Descending a Staircase or
at a rehearsal a single drawing of Leonardo or Michelangelo that used to wow me
and what good does all the research of the Impressionists do them
when they never got the right person to stand near the tree when the sun sank
or for that matter Marino Marini when he didn’t pick the rider as carefully
as the horse
                               it seems they were all cheated of some marvelous experience
which is not going to go wasted on me which is why I’m telling you about it

My goddaughter 6 years ago. Today I’m sitting in a cafe feeling so grateful.  My life has been a magnet - drawing love toward me - since I was born.  I’m so aware of how fortunate I am. All I want to do is keep sending out love and bathing in the reciprocation of it. 🫠💜

A peach colored rose. It’s a simple thing, yet a beautiful complex and impossible creation if you think about it. This is the only rose in my garden. One of one. I’ve never seen it before this week. In fact, I didn’t even know I had a rose bush on my property before it appeared.  Now, every day I see it I take a moment to be grateful; astonished that something so perfect and effortlessly beautiful could exist in this world. Thankful something with the ability to make me smile, just by thinking of it, is in the same universe as me at the same time I’m alive. Every time I walk out my front door and see it, my heart melts and I take that feeling with me out into the world.  I feel so grateful lately. My heart feels so open. Moments like this help to keep me in that mindset.

From @penguinukbooks We are delighted to announce the acquisition of World rights in a memoir from singer, songwriter and former front man of Savage Garden, Darren Hayes.
Share this
Darren Hayes is an iconic Australian singer, songwriter, music producer, composer and performer. Still performing on stages around the world, Darren is reflecting on his life story, with his book due for release in late 2024.

'I’ve been secretly telling stories about my life, through my music, since the very first Savage Garden single. Back then my innermost thoughts were shrouded in lyrical metaphor and deeply embedded within the visuals and stage costumes of a fantastical pop career. The reality of my life was much more complicated than the constraints of a 3 minute radio song would allow.  Almost 30 years later I feel free for the first time in my life and so grateful to partner with Penguin to truly tell my authentic story,' says Darren.

Alison Urquhart, Non-Fiction Publisher says 'I am thrilled to bits that we’ll be working together on this wonderful book.  Darren and I have a mutual love of 80s pop music and gothic, twisted tales and he is a remarkable and natural storyteller. I know that he will create something so special and a reflection of who he is both as an extraordinarily gifted artist and a remarkable human being.'
My first memoir will be released by @PenguinBooksAus @PenguinBooks in Late 2024. I'm so looking forward to sharing my stories with you.  Photo by @jamesreesephotography

I’ve known this woman since I was 21.  30 years. She recently spent a month with me in Los Angeles helping me transition my life into a new era.  Claire first showed up as the girl who ‘took my job’ at Woody’s Music Store (haha so not true - I left to become a pop star and then changed my mind when I saw how hard it was to sing cover songs 4 hours a night). Since then she went on to become an award winning choreographer who worked on all my tours and somehow showed up at every pivotal moment of my life including the moment when we almost ended up on one of the planes that sadly perished in September 11 but by the grace our our combined intuition - we did not. She is magical. She is empathy in human form.  I love you Claire. Here we are having our picture taken by someone who is love in human form.

All my life I’ve thought of myself as a diamond. Something strong and unbreakable forged from an early life of trauma and extreme pressure.  Like a diamond I chose to be unbreakable.  A diamond is an object to be admired. It’s a multifaceted precious object designed to reflect light coming toward it. To sparkle and inspire, scatter all the light being directed toward it - but never absorb any.  Well, I don’t want to be a diamond anymore.  I want to be a vessel that receives light, too, not just reflect it.  I want to give and receive love in equal measure. I’m learning to do that now. And it feels so good. 💎💡❤️🙃

I have so much to be thankful for. In a year when my entire life turned upside down I was met with such love and compassion.  Instead of falling apart I went with the flow, listened to my intuition and made brave decisions and as a result a whole new universe opened up to me.  Every step I’ve taken has been uncharted but driven by a desire to expand joy and give and receive love.  Today my world is smaller - but more authentic - and absolutely fortified with a rock solid belief that I’m safe, loved and valued by the people in it.  I’m so grateful to be alive.  Thank you for loving me. Te Amo.

From my home. 1999 @wafanasieff and myself singing in the Walter’s studio in San Francisco during the recording of the Affirmation album.  Although Daniel and I wrote the songs prior to getting into the studio with Walter - he only stayed for the recording of the musicians who played the various parts on the album then returned to Australia.  I remained for the entire process - doing most of my vocals with Walter and attending every day of the mix Dave Way.  Walter and and I became very close and soon after I moved to San Francisco and Marin Country - near his legendary recording studio ‘’Wallyworld’ in San Rafael. Beautiful memories. Walter was an absolute genius piano arranger and vocal producer. It’s his keyboard work you hear on songs like ‘Two Beds and a Coffee Machine’ and ‘I Knew I Loved You’ ps.
